# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ashley-rakahuri-regional-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area of the park has seen human interaction for approximately 700 years, with evidence of habitation dating back to early Māori iwi such as Waitaha and Rapuwai during the early periods of Māori habitation in New Zealand.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Following the arrival of Pākehā in the 19th century, the area saw widespread deforestation, farming, and quarrying, significantly modifying the area's environment.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this, the park is one of the most modified landscapes of any of New Zealand's national parks, with management of the park largely focusing on regeneration and restoration of the traditional ecosystem.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was first established in 1942 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's 1642 visit in New Zealand, when he became the first European to sight the islands.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It has since been progressively expanded from its original borders, the most recent of which involved the addition of 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet after a successful crowdfunding campaign.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The coastal area was inhabited for hundreds of years by Māori prior to the arrival of Europeans, with sites throughout the area occupied both seasonally and permanently.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In addition to harvesting food from the local forests, estuaries and waters, locals grew kūmara.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Historical records indicate a pā was established at Auckland Point by Pohea, who travelled there around 1450 from the Whanganui area.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] From the mid-1500s Muaūpoko (formerly known as Ngāi Tara) occupied the area until the early 1600s, when they were ousted by Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri were present when Abel Tasman reached Golden Bay / Mohua in 1642.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was founded in 1942, largely through the efforts of ornithologist and author Pérrine Moncrieff to have land reserved for the purpose.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Moncrieff served on the park board from 1943 to 1974.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was opened on 18 December 1942 to mark the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's visit.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Those in attendance at the opening ceremony at Tarakohe included Charles van der Plas, as personal representative of the Netherlands' Queen, Wilhelmina.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The idea for the park had been under consideration since June 1938.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Crown set aside 15,225 hectares (37,622 acres), comprising 8,900 hectares (21,900 acres) of proposed state forest, 5,809 hectares (14,354 acres) of Crown land and 554 hectares (1,368 acres) of other reserve land for the national park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Golden Bay Cement Company donated the land where the Abel Tasman Monument and a memorial plaque was sited.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area's primary historic interest was the visit of Tasman in 1642, D'Urville in 1827, and the New Zealand Company barques *Whitby* and *Will Watch*, and brig *Arrow* in 1841.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The site was also of significant botanical interest.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] By 1946 the park had reached 15,534 hectares (38,386 acres) in area with additional land purchases.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] A further 844 hectares (2,085 acres) at Tōtaranui, formerly owned by William Gibbs, was acquired from J S Campbell in 1949 and added to the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] About 6,100 hectares (15,000 acres) have been added since.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2008 an extra 7.9 km2 (790 ha; 3.1 sq mi), including the formerly private land known as Hadfields Clearing, were added to the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2016, a further 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet was purchased by New Zealanders in a crowdfunding campaign.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Covering an area of 237 km2 (92 sq mi; 59,000 acres), the park is the smallest of New Zealand's national parks.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It consists of forested, hilly country to the north of the valleys of the Tākaka and Riwaka Rivers, and is bounded to the north by the waters of Golden Bay / Mohua and Tasman Bay.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains some of the islands off the coast including the Tata Islands in Golden Bay / Mohua, and Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island, and Fisherman Island in Tasman Bay.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park does not extend beyond Mean High Water Mark on the adjacent coast.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Between Mean High Water and Mean Low Water Springs, the beaches are gazetted as a Scenic Reserve, covering 7.74 km2 (2.99 sq mi) in total.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Tonga Island Marine Reserve adjoins part of the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Monument, though not located in the park, commemorates the first contact between Europeans and Māori and is located near the northern end of the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Abel Tasman National Park stands out from most other National parks of New Zealand, given that a large area of it has undergone extensive environmental modification in its history.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Early European settlers burned or cleared much of the forest, only to find that the soil was unsuitable for farming.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This practise not only destroyed much of the shrubland and forests, but also introduced invasive plants found throughout the modern-day park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] However, as time progresses, the original ecosystems and forests are slowly returning.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains varied habitats, including coastal forests, sub-alpine bogs, and sand dunes.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this diversity, many different species can be found.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The islands of the park, in particular Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island and Fisherman Island which are the largest, have been disturbed less and have no introduced mammalian predators.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result the islands have species not found elsewhere in the park and there are more restrictions to visitor access.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Though much of the parkland is pasture or covered with shrubs, valley areas contain forests of rātā, mataī, miro and hinau.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Over 70 species of birds have been recorded in the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Some of the birds that can frequently be seen are petrels, shags, penguins, gulls, terns, and herons.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Possums, wild pigs, deer, and goats can also be seen in the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Coast Track is a popular tramping track that follows the coastline and is one of the Department of Conservation's Great Walks; the Abel Tasman Inland Track is less frequented.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Other walks in the park, such as the Wainui Falls Track are considered "short walks".
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Kayaking, camping and sightseeing are other activities.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Access to the park is usually via the small settlement of Mārahau or Kaiteriteri (by water taxi).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The nearest large town is Motueka, 20 kilometres (12 mi) to the south.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Dogs (excepting guide dogs) are not allowed in the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation administers the National Park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Scenic Reserve is administered by the Tasman District Council Chief Executive and Department of Conservation's Nelson / Marlborough Conservator.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Activities in adjoining coastal waters are Tasman District Council's responsibility.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] These areas operate under separate regulations.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Interior, consisting of the park areas further inland.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Park plans include ecological surveys, pest control, and protection of heritage areas and caves.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Islands, encompassing all islands within the park, some of which are closed to the public. key priorities include keeping them free of invasive pests, reintroducing native species, and minimizing human impacts.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2012 Project Janszoon, a privately funded trust, was set up to restore the park's ecosystems.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The trust takes its name from Tasman's middle name *Janszoon*.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It is aiming to complete the restoration in time for the 400th anniversary of Tasman's visit and the park's 100th anniversary in 2042.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation and Project Janszoon developed a free virtual visitor centre for downloading to smartphones or tablets.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The application provides information about the Park's history, its flora and fauna, points of interest, weather, walking tracks, and tides.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This virtual visitor centre is free of charge and can be found through the App Store or Google Play Store.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The mountains, forests, tussock lands and river valleys are used for tramping, fishing kayaking, horse riding and hunting.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Both the park and neighbouring Ben Avon Station are located near the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve, a dark-sky preserve, and are used for astronomy.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The town is serviced by the tourist town of Omarama.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The park was established in 2005, and includes the Birchwood Station leasehold farm the New Zealand Government bought back for NZ$10 million in 2004.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] It contained extensive wetlands that had remained largely undeveloped.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Birchwood Station continued normal farming operations until the end of the leasehold in 2010.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The road to the former Birchwood Station homestead stopped being regularly maintained by Waitaki District Council in 2011.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] In 2014, ecologist Peter Espie reported a decrease in native plant species in the park, and suggested introducing grazing management.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Parts of the 2020 Disney film *Mulan* were filmed in the Ahuriri Valley near the conservation park, including the training camp scenes and some battle scenes.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Akaroa Marine Reserve and the nearby Pōhatu Marine Reserve are no-take zones.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The harbour as a whole has considerable natural values, and the fauna of the inner and outer harbour differs.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are pressures on the ecology from human activity, such as settlements on the edge of the harbour, and land and water-based industrial activity.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The marine boundary of Akaroa Marine Reserve is almost entirely surrounded by Akaroa Taiāpure, which occupies the rest of the harbour and the ocean coast between the Akaroa and Pōhatu reserves.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure is a local fishing co-management tool for the harbour, which has customarily been of special significance to the hapū as a source of food for spiritual and cultural reasons.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established over 90 percent of the harbour in February 2006.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] It allows Te Rūnanga o Ngāi Tahu (tribal council) and other fisheries stakeholders to have a say in how the harbour is managed.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishing can continue in taiāpure, subject to rules and regulations.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure complements the reserve (the remaining 10% of the harbour), as does Pōhatu Marine Reserve just outside the harbour entrance, in Pōhatu / Flea Bay, plus Lyttelton Harbour's Port Levy Mātaitai Reserve and Rāpaki Mātaitai Reserve.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A *mātaitai* is a permanent reserve created in areas of traditional importance to Māori for customary food gathering.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The two marine reserves are total no-take areas, whereas the taiāpure and mātaitai are fishing enabling and not about the protection of marine life.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Indeed, the *tangata tiaki* (marine guardian) has the power to override fishing regulations, and moreover, the taking of kelp by one pāua farmer is enshrined in the taiāpure legislation.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Taiāpure Management Committee is a non-elected group largely made up of Ngāi Tahu representatives and a range of fisheries interest groups, including recreational, commercial, marine farmers and marine tourism operators.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This committee has no control over the number of recreational anglers, hence no control over the total number of fish and shellfish taken.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, people with local knowledge knew that fish stocks were nowhere near as plentiful as they once were.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Māori who had fished the harbour for decades had lost the opportunity of fishing freely along its shoreline.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The *rūnanga* (committee of senior decision-makers of an *iwi* (tribal group) or *hapū* (family, district groups or community)) knew that pollution and over-fishing had diminished the area of available *mahinga kai* (traditional food gathering areas) within the harbour.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Pollution includes sewage, farm and sub-division run-off as well as algal blooms.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Forest and Bird carried out exploratory dives in Akaroa Harbour in 1990.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Harbour Marine Protection Society formally proposed the establishment of a 560-hectare (1,400-acre) marine reserve in 1996.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The proposal was divisive and led to a two-decade battle that pitted a small group of vocal and determined local residents and divers against recreational anglers, *rūnanga*, commercial fishers and one aquaculturalist.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The local residents wanted a no-take area in the eastern waters of the outer harbour to acts as a breeding pool and as place for dolphins to feed.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Recreational anglers argued "that's where we fish in a northeasterly".
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Te Runanga o Ngāi Tahu claimed strong ties to the area, naming it Te Whata o Kōkiro (meaning the food store-house of Kokiro).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] When the marine reserve idea was first mooted, commercial fishing was a part of Akaroa's economy and commercial fishers strongly opposed it.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] During the long battle, fish stock declined, and so did commercial fishing.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The original proposal called for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers counteracted that proposal by applying for and getting a smaller 215 hectares (530 acres) hectares reserve to be located outside of the harbour, at sheltered bay named Pōhatu / Flea Bay.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] While eco-tourism operators were pleased to have something to show to tourists, local iwi continued to express concerns that marine reserves hindered their traditional rights to harvest from the sea.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Meanwhile, the local residents group continued to advocate for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Fisheries Act 1996 Part 9 Section 174–175 provides for the establishment of taiāpure/fisheries co-management by local people who care about and have strong ties to an area.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In January 2004, the Māori Land Court tribunal made a recommendation to the Minister of Fisheries that a taiāpure be granted over the whole of Akaroa Harbour bar one small area subject to the, at that time, proposed Akaroa Marine Reserve.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Judge Wainwright saw no reason why the two could not live together.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, this recommendation was successfully appealed by the local pāua farmer and kelp harvester, who claimed a taiāpure would compromise his business.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The High Court sent the case back to the tribunal to gather further evidence about whether the whole of Akaroa Harbour does or does not come within the concept of "littoral coastal waters" of "special cultural significance" to the rūnanga.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The pāua farmer eventually reached an understanding with Ngāi Tahu, ending years of argument.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] He has been granted the rights to harvest giant bladder kelp (*Macrocystis pyrifera*), which he uses to feed the pāua at the Akaroa Paua Farm and also to make garden fertiliser and kelp pepper.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In contrast, the East Otago Taiāpure explicitly prohibits the harvesting of kelp.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] That ban does not extend to unattached beach-cast kelp.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are environmental concerns in Akaroa Harbour regarding the ecological disruption caused by kelp harvesting to wild pāua and other *kaimoana* (sea food).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established in February 2006, but the marine reserve took eight more years.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Conservation Minister Kate Wilkinson declined the application for the reserve in 2010 on the grounds that it would adversely affect recreational fishing.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The decision was challenged in the High Court and was quashed in a 2012 ruling.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In terms of actual numbers, the two separate consultation processes for the application had attracted more support than opposition.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In April 2013 Conservation Minister Nick Smith announced the approval of the reserve but at the reduced size of 465 hectares (1,150 acres).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Smith believed the battle had gone on for too long.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The size was reduced to take into account the concerns about customary and recreational fishing.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Subsequently, the size was finalised as 512 hectares (1,270 acres).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Environment Minister Amy Adams expressed an aspiration for the next step to be integrating the local management of taiāpure and reserve so the two mechanisms work together.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] New Zealand fishing rules place reduced bag limits on many fish species and prohibit shellfish gathering in specific areas.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Tangata tiaki (marine guardians) are appointed for Ōnuku Runanga *rōhe moana* (defined customary fishing area) by the Minister of Primary Industries.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The tangata tiaki (also known as kaitiaki) receive training in bylaws, what quantities of various species can be taken, dates or seasons recommended for harvest, size limits and methods of harvest.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers can get a kaitiaki permit from the tangata tiaki granting permission to take over and above the catch limit, and under the legal size.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This permit, colloquially called a "chit", is given for *tangihanga* (funeral), *hui* (gathering) and other occasions.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In addition to upping catch limits, the kaitiaki has the power to override other fishing regulations.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2018, the Department of Conservation trialled a baited underwater video study, which provided a snapshot of the fish communities both within and outside the Akaroa and Pōhatu marine reserves.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A total of 28 fish species were identified, demonstrating that the baited underwater video technique is an effective method for examining the size and relative abundance of these species.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The study found notable differences in the relative abundances and sizes of blue cod and blue moki in the marine reserves when compared to three taiāpure control areas.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, since there is no baseline data for Akaroa Marine Reserve, it would be hasty to link these spatial variations to their protection status.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Nonetheless, the results indicated an increase in the abundance and size of blue cod and moki at Pōhatu reserve compared to earlier studies, and that is likely due to the protection from direct fishing pressure.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2021, a three-year initiative called *Iongairo* was launched to supply data that aids in the management of customary fishing zones and enhances understanding of marine reserves in Te Pātaka o Rākaihautū/Banks Peninsula.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] *Iongairo* focused on identifying and evaluating important habitats—including rock, sand, and mud—and key species such as pāua, mussels, and various types of seaweed.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Additionally, it examined the effects of human activities on the environment.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Methods included baited underwater cameras, towed and dropped cameras, along with sediment grabs.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The outcome is an interactive online map showcasing the seafloor.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] The park is owned and managed by Greater Wellington Regional Council, making it one of the largest landowners in New Zealand.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa is a Māori name meaning 'Trailing vines'.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Activities include cycling, hunting, fishing, horse riding, 4WD-vehicle trips and trail biking, including at the Karapoti Gorge.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa Forest has ancient northern rātā which predate human habitation of New Zealand, including one tree which is believed to be 1100 years old.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Some of these trees are wider than Tāne Mahuta.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] One is largest rātā tree in New Zealand, at 39 metres tall.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Greater Wellington Regional Council carried out a 1080 dropping programme in 2013 to reduce pest species.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] A trailbiker was seriously injured in the park in July 2017.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] A dirt-biker was rescued from the forest in February 2021.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] Between December 2017 and August 2018, a 1.7 kilometre zig-zag track that is part of the Cannon Point Walkway was closed to the public due to a disagreement between Upper Hutt City Council and a private landowner over land access.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] In early 2021, Forest and Bird campaigned for Upper Hutt City Council to keep a 35-hectare block as a wildlife corridor and reserve, connecting Akatarawa Forest with Wainuiomata.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/akatarawa-forest] In July 2021, a further 1080 operation was carried out in 2021 to combat a resurgence in possum numbers.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The area was previously a defensive pā, built by Te Kawerau sub-tribes, occupied until as recently as 1827.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Ngāti Pāoa ceded the land to the Crown on 5 January 1854, which was subsequently granted to an Austrian, Captain Martin Krippner, in 1860.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In the 1870s, Major de Grut took over the land until it was sold to the Eaves family in 1919.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The local Lions began making tracks, building bridges and removing invasive weeds, and the Reserve was formally opened by the Lions Club Chairman, Don Woods on 10 December 1960.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The daughters of Alice and Edward Eaves were present.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] A series of pedestrian walkways have been constructed through the reserve, as well as a wooden look out point over Orewa Beach that was built in 1997.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The reserve includes kauri trees as old as 300 years.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In addition, the bush contains native trees such as tōtara, mataī, kahikatea, pūriri, rata, karaka, rimu, rewarewa, nīkau and taraire.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] A number of these trees can be identified by labels along the walkway.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Several small streams feed the Nukumea Stream, which marks the reserve's southern boundary.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The status of the land is Scenic Reserve 19(1)(a) and under the Reserves Act, the management is the responsibility of the Hibiscus and Bays Local Board, elected representatives under the Governing Body, Auckland Council.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The role of the Board is to make decisions on local matters such as the maintenance and upgrading of facilities, caring for the environment, preservation of heritage and supporting activities in the area.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In June 2019, the Reserve was required by the Auckland Council to close to the public due to the danger of kauri dieback caused by the spread of a pathogen in contaminated soil possibly being carried on the soles of shoes.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Lauri Rands from the Eaves Bush Appreciation Society expressed sadness but noted that protection of the 800-year-old kauri in the Reserve was a good example of the importance of taking this action.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The lower track on the Reserve was re-opened on 30 August 2020 with a hygiene station at the entrance and exit to allow shoes to be cleaned.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] It was noted at the time, that the upper tracks were scheduled for re-opening late in 2021.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Hibiscus and Bays Local Board Chair Gary Brown expressed delight at the reopening and appreciation to the Council for the work they had done to bring this about.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] He also acknowledged the voluntary contribution of the Eaves Bush Appreciation Group who had worked for years to weed, plant and trap pests.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Members of this group were the first to walk the re-opened section.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The Greenways project proposed by the Auckland Council in 2016 had been prioritised by the Hisbiscus and Bays Local Board in 2017 and a feasibility report for implementing walking and cycling connections between the Reserve and Hatfields Beach was completed in 2018.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The park is a working sheep and dairy farm with a woolshed and milking shed.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] There are also goats, cows, pigs, chickens, turkey, rabbits and peacocks.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Areas of the park are leased to the Mangere Pony Club, and the Ambury Park Centre for Riding Therapy, a charity which opened in 1985, which provides physiological and psychological therapy through horse riding.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The parks hosts the Ambury Farm Day each year.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] It is the largest annual event organised by Auckland Council, and gives families free access to a working farm.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The park covers 85 hectares (210 acres) of low-lying volcanic land on the shores of the upper Manukau Harbour.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] It includes both camping coastline, grazed farming paddocks, wetlands, saltmarshes and small areas of native forest.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Much of Ambury Regional Park formed approximately 50,000 years ago, during an eruption of Māngere Mountain.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] There are several examples of basalt lava flows, originating from the Māngere Mountain about 18,000 years ago.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Most other lava flows around Auckland have been destroyed during urban development.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Large numbers of migratory shorebirds visit Ambury Regional Park and the surrounding areas of the Manukau Harbour, with an estimated number of 28,000 tōrea and 1,200 ngutuparore (wrybills) migrating north from the South Island after breeding over the winter.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] During summer months, an estimated 12,000 kuaka (bar-tailed godwits) and 9,000 huahou (red knots) spend summer months in the vicinity of the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Kōtuku ngutupapa (royal spoonbill) also migrate to the area.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Birdwatchers have identified a total of 86 birds in the park including little shags, and white-faced herons.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In 2015, a vegetation survey identified 40 native species in Ambury Regional Park, including the nationally vulnerable species *Geranium retrorsum*, and oioi-coastal needle grass, only rarely seen in saline volcanic soil in the Auckland Region.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] There is an extensive history of Māori settlement in the Māngere Mountain area, and there are 95 archaeological sites around the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] During the mid-19th century, the area was converted to farmland.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In 1882, the Ambury English & Co milk company established a creamery on a 260 acres (110 ha) farm on Wallace Road.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In the late 1960s, the Māngere sewage treatment was established on the shores of the Manukau Harbour.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Over 500 hectares (1,200 acres) of oxidation ponds were decommissioned, 13 kilometres (8.1 mi) of shoreline were restored, beaches were constructed, and 27,000 trees were planted in New Zealand's largest coastal restoration project, which was officially completed in 2005.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] During the 1960s, the Auckland Regional Authority purchased land adjacent to the Māngere sewage treatment plant as a buffer.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] From une 1973, local community groups were able to user the land, and in 1977 an educational farm was established at the site.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] Ambury Regional Park was officially opened on 26 September 1987.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In 1985, a fuel pipeline between Marsden Point and Auckland Airport was laid through the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The route is marked by white fenceposts, farm gate tags and triangular marine markers.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] In December 1986, the Ambury Regional Park was the site of a large-scale Mongrel Mob convention, where over 300 members attended, during which gang members helped complete the rock retaining walls along the Manukau waterfront.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] A kidnapping and sexual assault at this event became national news.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The annual Ambury Farm Day began in 1988.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] By the early 2000s, the park had become a popular school excursion, with 3-4 schools booked per week visiting the working farm.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] A new concept plan for the park was developed in 2009, which included linking it up to nearby walk and cycling tracks.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] By that stage, 25,000 people were visiting the park each year outside of the annual farm day.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] By the late 2010s, around 400,000 people had begun visiting the park annually.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] There are a range of facilities, including public toilets and barbecues.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The campground can accommodate up to 60 people.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] The park is connected by walkway and cycleway to the Māngere Bridge to Onehunga in the north-east along Kiwi Esplanade, and the Ihumātao to the south.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ambury-regional-park] It is within walking distance to the nearest bus stop, and the nearest train station is Onehunga railway station.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] The regional park an area Ashley River / Rakahuri and Okuku River, including pine forest blocks and mixed stands of exotic trees like willows and poplar.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] Pockets of native vegetation are gradually being restored.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] Ashley River is steeper than other braided rivers in New Zealand, moving large amounts of sediment.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] It breached its stopbanks in 1953 next to the Rangiora Traffic Bridge, causing flooding in Rangiora, Kaiapoi, Woodend and Waikuku causing large amounts of damage.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] River engineering and protection work has been carried out since then to prevent similar flooding events.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] The land of the Ashley Rakahuri Regional Park was vested in Environment Canterbury to protect that work.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] The first areas of the regional park were formally opened on 14 October 2012.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] In July 2020, Environment Canterbury felled 500 trees in the reserve without community consultation.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] In January 2021, a group of motorcyclists and four-wheel-drivers rode through a colony of nesting black-billed gulls in the park, killing several rare birds.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] In June 2021, parts of the park were closed due to flooding.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] The park has a range of places of fishing, swimming, game-bird hunting, walking, cycling and picnicking.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] Dogs are allowed but must be kept under control at all times.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] Gas barbecues are allowed away from vegetation, but there are no on-site barbecues and there is a complete ban on fires.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] The Mike Kean Walkway connects the State Highway 1 road bridge and the rail bridge.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] The Rakahuri Trail, a shared mountain biking and walking track, follows the river downstream from Groyne 1, with shorter single-track mountain bike tracks branch off.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] The main track is a two-way shared path with loose compact shingle.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] In October 2017, Rakahuri Trail was extended to Waikuku Beach, doubling its length.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] The North Canterbury BMX Club has tracks that can be accessed off Milton Ave.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] The most popular access points for the regional park are at the Rangiora/Ashley traffic bridge and State Highway 1 bridge.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/ashley-rakahuri-regional-park] There are carparks on River Road, the Ashley picnic site, Break Bank, the rail bridge, and the Rakahuri picnic area.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] At the end of the most recent ice age approximately 13000 years ago, numerous glaciers in the park were tributaries of a much larger glacier covering all of Hooker Valley and Tasman Valley in hundreds of metres of ice.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] This glacier reached beyond the southern end of today's Lake Pukaki, up to 40 km (25 mi) south of Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] As it retreated, it filled the hollowed-out valleys, leaving behind the U-shaped valleys seen today in the national park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Early European surveyors and explorers ventured into the alpine region surrounding Aoraki / Mount Cook from the 1850s.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Many of the geographical features in the national park were named by or after them.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Ngāi Tahu Claims Settlement Act passed in October 1998 recognised the original names of some geographical features, establishing dual English / Māori names.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park is home to more than four hundred species of plants, including more than one hundred introduced species.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are about thirty-five species of birds in the park, most notably the rare black stilt and pīwauwau.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The only road access into the park is via State Highway 80 which starts 65 km (40 mi) away near Twizel, the closest town, and leads directly to Mount Cook Village along the western shore of Lake Pukaki.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mount Cook Aerodrome is a small airfield located 5 km (3.1 mi) southeast of Mount Cook Village within the national park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park is a popular tourist destination.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are numerous walking tracks, the most popular being the Hooker Valley Track, a relatively short track that takes around three hours to complete.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park is also popular with astrophotographers and star-gazers because of the low levels of light pollution.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] An area including Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park and the Mackenzie Basin was designated as the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve in June 2012.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The national park has been used as a filming location for numerous films.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In Māori mythology, Aoraki was one of the sons of Raki the Sky Father.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] One version of the legend states that Aoraki came down from heaven in a canoe with three of his brothers, Rakiroa, Rakirua and Rārakiroa, to visit his father Raki's new wife Papatūānuku, but the *waka* (canoe) overturned.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The brothers climbed on to the overturned canoe, becoming the mountains Aoraki / Mount Cook, Rakiroa (Mount Dampier), Rakirua (Mount Teichelmann) and Rārakiroa (Mount Tasman).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The *waka* itself became the Southern Alps (*Kā Tiritiri o te Moana*).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Although there is no evidence of permanent or temporary Māori settlement within the national park, some artefacts and evidence of burnt vegetation have been found in the nearby Mackenzie Basin.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] These may be related to nomadic parties who would spend months here hunting moa or fighting other parties.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Māori would burn tōtara forests to assist them with their hunting of moa and gathering food, mostly weka, eels and kiore, before heading to the West Coast in search of *pounamu*.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1896, mountaineer Arthur Harper wrote that Māori had a deep-seated fear of the mountains and preferred to stay lower down in the valleys.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] However, Māori did have knowledge of the various features of high alpine areas, with special words for different types of ice and snow.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Historian Johannes Carl Andersen believed it was possible that Māori had travelled over the Main Divide, which is at the northern boundary of Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park, to trade *pounamu*.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] According to log entries made by explorer Abel Tasman, it is likely that he and his crew sighted the Southern Alps in December 1642 from the Tasman Sea near Barrytown.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1770 Captain James Cook sailed along the West Coast of the South Island.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] He sighted and named the Southern Alps but probably did not sight Aoraki.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki was given the name Mount Cook by Captain Stokes of the survey ship HMS *Acheron* in 1851, to honour James Cook's circumnavigation of New Zealand.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1998, the Ngāi Tahu Claims Settlement Act officially recognised the original names of the geographical features of Ngāi Tahu's *takiwā* (tribal area), establishing dual English and Māori names such as Kirikirikatata / Mount Cook Range and Haupapa / Tasman Glacier.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Europeans have had interest in the national park since the 1850s; public appreciation of the alpine regions surrounding Aoraki / Mount Cook grew with the maps and reports produced by early European surveyors and explorers.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Julius von Haast explored the area at the head of Lakes Tekapo, Pukaki and Ōhau in 1862, collecting specimens, making maps and writing comprehensive reports on his observations, and, starting in 1867, surveyor Edward Sealy explored many glaciers.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Many of the peaks, glaciers and other geographical features of the region were named by or for these early explorers, such as the Sealy Tarns track being named after Edward Sealy and the Mueller Glacier named after Ferdinand von Mueller.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Public appreciation of the mountains also grew as images of the area began to circulate.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Artists painted pictures, and from 1867–1870 Sealy photographed the Mount Cook region.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1873 the then Governor of New Zealand, Sir George Bowen, visited the Mount Cook region, thereby further raising the profile of the area.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Parts of Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park were first set aside as a recreation reserve in 1885, and the national park was established in October 1953.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1990, the park (along with Westland Tai Poutini, Mount Aspiring and Fiordland National Parks) became part of the Te Wahipounamu World Heritage Site, the first place in New Zealand to attain World Heritage Status.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Following the settlement between Ngāi Tahu and the Crown in October 1998, a number of South Island place names were amended by the Ngāi Tahu Claims Settlement Act 1998 to incorporate their Māori names.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The name of the mountain village and national park were officially changed from Mount Cook to Aoraki / Mount Cook.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Efforts to protect the alpine environment began in the 19th century.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] A petition addressed to James Sutter, a member of Parliament, was circulated in November 1884, requesting that the Government protect the alpine region around Aoraki / Mount Cook.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Petitioners were concerned that stock grazing and burn-offs were destroying the native bush and vegetation of the area.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The petitioners suggested that Frank Huddleston, who had recently bought land at the base of the Mueller Glacier and was building the Hermitage, be appointed as a ranger to oversee the area.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In January 1885 the Hooker and Mueller Valleys were gazetted as the Hooker Glacier Recreation Reserve.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1887 the Government permanently reserved an area of 97,800 acres of the Tasman Valley above the Mueller Valley confluence, which was known as the Tasman Recreation Reserve or Tasman Park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Hooker Glacier reserve was expanded in 1890, becoming the 38,000-acre Aorangi Domain.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1953, Tasman Park and Aorangi Domain became the Mount Cook National Park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park as established covered 151,780 acres (614.2 km2) of the Southern Alps, including the Mueller, Hooker, and Tasman glaciers and the eastern slopes of Aoraki / Mount Cook and Mount Tasman.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park is managed by the Department Of Conservation and Ngāi Tahu, the iwi who hold *mana whenua* status of the land.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park stretches for about 60 km (37 mi) along the southwest–northeast direction of the Southern Alps, covering 722 km2 (279 sq mi) on the south-eastern side of the main spine of the Alps.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Of New Zealand's 20 peaks over 3,000 m (9,800 ft), all except Mount Aspiring / Tititea lie within the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] These include New Zealand's highest mountain, Aoraki / Mount Cook, at 3,724 m (12,218 ft).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Other prominent peaks in or nearby the national park include Mount Tasman, Mount Hicks, Mount Sefton and Mount Elie de Beaumont.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] At the end of the most recent ice age around 13,000 years ago, numerous glaciers were tributaries of a much larger glacier covering all of Hooker Tasman Valleys in hundreds of metres of ice.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] This glacier was about 85 km (53 mi) long and reached beyond the southern end of today's Lake Pukaki, up to 40 km (25 mi) south of Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] As the glacier retreated, it filled the hollowed-out valleys with rocks and gravel, leaving behind the flat-bottomed U-shaped valleys seen today.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Moraines left behind by the glacier's retreat can be seen in the valleys.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Glaciers cover 40% of the park area, notably the Tasman Glacier in the Tasman Valley east of Aoraki / Mount Cook which is the largest glacier in New Zealand.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] A majority of glaciers in New Zealand lie within Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park, such as the Tasman Glacier, Hooker Glacier, Murchison Glacier and Mueller Glacier, while further north in the park lie the Godley Glacier, Classen Glacier, Grey Glacier and Maud Glacier.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] All of these glaciers terminate at proglacial lakes formed in recent decades due to a sustained period of shrinking.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tasman Lake and Hooker Lake are easily accessible via walking tracks and are the only two of these lakes that have official names.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tasman Lake is the largest of the proglacial lakes.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Taking a boat tour among the icebergs on the Tasman Lake is a popular tourist activity.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Temperatures in Mount Cook Village range between extremes of −13 °C (9 °F) to 32 °C (90 °F), and typically fall just over 1 °C (34 °F) for every 200 metres (660 ft) of additional altitude.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Rainfall is similarly variable, with the driest months receiving around 300 mm (12 in) precipitation, but recorded maxima are 537 mm (21.1 in) in one day and 1,447 mm (57.0 in) in a single month.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] During the coldest months of the year, Mueller Glacier Lake, Hooker Lake, and Tasman Lake usually freeze over, at least partially.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The weather conditions in the park, in particular at higher altitudes, can be unpredictable and change rapidly.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Southern Alps lie along a geological plate boundary, with the Pacific Plate to the southeast pushing westward and colliding with the northward-moving Indo-Australian Plate to the northwest.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook lies in the centre of the Alpine Fault, a 600 km (370 mi) long active fault formed by the plate boundary, which has ruptured four times in the last 900 years.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Over the last 45 million years, the collision of the two tectonic plates has pushed up a 25 km thickness of rocks on the Pacific Plate to form the Southern Alps.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Extreme temperatures and high precipitation work to shatter surface rock, leading to erosion down the steep slopes.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In December 1991, an avalanche of 10 million cubic metres of snow and rock caused 10 metres to be lost off the top of Aoraki / Mount Cook.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Two decades of erosion of the ice cap exposed after this collapse reduced the height by another 30 m to 3,724 m, as revealed by GPS data from a University of Otago climbing expedition in November 2013.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are two main rock types in the Southern Alps: sedimentary sandstones and metamorphic schists.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The sandstones are greywacke and argillite, mostly to the east of the Main Divide, whereas the schists are mostly to the west of the Main Divide.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Rock along the Alpine Fault has been warped and folded into complex layers with much shearing and fracturing.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Very few fossils have been found in the rocks of the national park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Parts of the Malte Brun range can be dated to the Permian Period by fossils found there in red argillite.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] More than 400 species of plants are found in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park, including more than 100 introduced plant species such as the colourful Russell lupin, wild cherry, snowberries, and wilding pines.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Most parts of the national park are either at higher altitude or in the proglacial valleys such as the Hooker Valley and Tasman Valley, where the soil of the valley floors and moraine walls do not support forest growth.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] As a result, the only pockets of forest and native bush, such as silver beech and tōtara trees, can be found in the park are along the southern edge of the Hooker Valley and the lower slopes of Sealy Range.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The plant life in the majority of the park consists mostly of alpine plants.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] All of these plants flower in the warmer months from November to February – early in the season in the valley floors, and later at higher altitudes.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] At the highest rocks of Aoraki / Mount Cook, around 14 species of lichen have been found.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The native vegetation continues to be under threat by introduced plant species ranging from non-native trees through to lupins, broom and non-native grasses.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] These are mostly contained in the valley floors of the Tasman and Hooker Valley, since they are the most accessible parts of the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tutu, a poisonous plant, flourishes throughout the Hooker Valley during summer.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tutu is considered *taonga* by Ngāi Tahu.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are about 35 species of birds in the park including the kea, the only alpine parrot, Australasian Harrier (*kāhu*), silvereye (*tauhou*), a small omnivorous passerine bird, New Zealand falcon (*kārearea*), and the pipit (*pīhoihoi*).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The tiny New Zealand rock wren (*pīwauwau*), a threatened species, is the only permanent alpine bird in New Zealand.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Small insectivores such as the rifleman (*tītipounamu*) and the fantail (*pīwakawaka*) live in the low forest and scrub, along with small numbers of two larger birds, the kererū and morepork (*ruru*).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Introduced species such as finches and sparrows live throughout the bush near Mount Cook Village.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The black stilt (*kakī*), the rarest wading bird in the world, primarily lives in the braided riverbed of the Tasman Valley.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 2019, young black stilts raised in a hatchery were released near the Cass River and Godley River.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] European explorer Julius von Haast reported seeing kākā and piopio in the national park in 1862, however the piopio later became extinct.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park is home to many invertebrates, including large dragonflies, crickets, grasshoppers, 223 recorded moth species and 7 native butterflies.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The black alpine wētā, also known as the Mount Cook flea, is found above the snowline.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The jewelled gecko lives in the park but is rarely seen.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Access to the national park began as a rough track from Twizel along the western shore of Lake Pukaki to the Hermitage.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The road, now known as State Highway 80, was improved over time.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In the 1960s a major hydroelectric scheme was underway in the Mackenzie Basin.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] This required Lake Pukaki to be raised by 37 m (121 ft), which would submerge parts of the gravel road to the Hermitage, so a new sealed road was built and completed in 1975.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The highway ends at Mount Cook Village, with a connecting road leading to the White Horse Hill camping ground.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Another small road leads to a car park near Tasman Lake, the start of a short walking track and the Ball Hut Route.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] A pedestrian swing bridge was built over the Hooker River in the Hooker Valley in 1911, providing easier access to climbing routes.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Rodolph Wigley's Mount Cook Motor Co was formed in 1906 to provide passenger and mail services to the Hermitage from the railhead at Fairlie.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The first coaches held between five and nine passengers and the journey from Fairlie to the Hermitage took around seven hours, not including a meal break.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The service evolved into Mount Cook Landlines, which transported visitors to Mount Cook Village from Queenstown and Christchurch until 1989.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1989, the new owner of Mount Cook Landlines, Tourism Holdings Limited, scrapped the coach services and the *Mount Cook* brand.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In recent years, coach services to Mount Cook Village are run by InterCity and other smaller operators.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1920, following his success running a bus service to Mount Cook Village, Rodolph Wigley raised the idea of providing flights from Timaru and Queenstown to Mount Cook.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] A test flight took place in May 1920, with a plane circling Aoraki / Mount Cook but not landing, but nothing came of the idea.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The first landing in the Mount Cook area took place on 4 December 1934.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] White and a passenger flew a Spartan from Timaru, landing at Birch Hill Flat, 5 km (3.1 mi) southeast of Mount Cook Village.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Wigley's Mount Cook Tourist Company then built a small airfield, Mount Cook Aerodrome, at Birch Hill Flat.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] There is also another airfield, Glentanner Aerodrome, which is 20 km (12 mi) from Mount Cook Village.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mount Cook Airline began scheduled passenger flights to the area in 1961.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In December 2019, Mount Cook Airline was merged into Air New Zealand and ceased operations.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Mount Cook company developed retractable skis for small aircraft, providing direct access to snowfields for skiers and sightseers.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The first ski plane flight using retractable skis took place in 1955.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mount Cook Ski-Planes and Helicopters is now an independently operated company, offering landings on the Tasman Glacier.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Helicopters also provide access to the mountains for hunters and climbers.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Ski touring is also possible on the Tasman Glacier, the descent from the top to the bottom is about 19 km (12 mi).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The village contains a small visitor centre, housing and amenities for the staff of the hotel and motels and other support personnel.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The village has a small public primary school, opened in 1960, which is the only school in New Zealand situated inside a national park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1884, Frank Huddleston opened accommodation he called "The Hermitage" at a site near the Mueller Glacier, to cater for climbing parties visiting the area.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The hotel was later expanded, but was severely damaged by two floods in 1913.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Hermitage was rebuilt on a more elevated site, opening in 1914, but that building was destroyed by fire in 1957.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] It was rebuilt quickly, opening in 1958, and since then has been altered and expanded several times as tourism increased.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] A visitor centre in the village features interpretation exhibits about the area's natural environment and history as well as an artwork collection.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park attracted over one million tourists in 2019, a significant increase compared to the three hundred ninety-eight thousand people that visited in the 2016/2017 season.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tourism significantly decreased after the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park is a popular location for day hikes, sightseeing flights, heliskiing, hunting, kayaking, mountaineering, ski touring and tramping.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Department of Conservation, alongside Ngāi Tahu, administers all activities in the park, including the White Horse Hill camping ground.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Recreational helicopter flights and sightseeing planes operate in the national park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park also attracts astrophotographers and stargazers due to low light pollution in the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mount Cook Village is the start of several walking tracks, such as the popular Hooker Valley track which is 10 km (6.2 mi) long (return) and typically takes three hours to complete.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] About 1800–2000 people a day walk the Hooker Valley track in the peak season.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Sealy Tarns is another popular track in the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] It is more challenging than the Hooker Valley track, and is nicknamed "The Stairway to Heaven" due to its steepness.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Guided walking tours are offered on some other tracks, and boat trips and kayaking tours for tourists take place on the Tasman Lake at the end of the glacier.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The park contains 15 huts, mostly in alpine terrain.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The huts range from basic shelters to serviced huts, with the most accessible being Mueller Hut, which can be reached from Mount Cook Village within four hours.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In February 2024, the Department of Conservation reported that 250 people per day were using the track to Mueller Hut, mostly as day-walkers.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The large number of visitors led to the toilets at the hut nearing maximum capacity.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The track was temporarily closed to day-walkers so that those with a hut booking could still access and use the hut.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park is the starting point of the Alps to Ocean Cycle Trail to Oamaru.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The 300 km (190 mi) cycle trail was constructed from 2010 onwards by the New Zealand Cycle Trail project.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] As of 2016 the cycle trail still includes 15 km (9.3 mi) along public roads.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The peaks of the Aoraki / Mount Cook region have long attracted mountaineers.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] William Spotswood Green made the first notable attempt to climb Aoraki / Mount Cook.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Green travelled to New Zealand with two Swiss guides to make the climb, after seeing Sealy's photographs of the mountain at an exhibition in London.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The three men got very close to the summit before being forced to turn back.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] At a dinner in his honour after the climb, Green noted that climbing would be easier if huts were built in the mountains, as the huts would provide shelter and a place to store provisions, lightening the load of climbers.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] He also suggested that New Zealand set up an Alpine Club, leading to establishment of the New Zealand Alpine Club in 1891.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] After several attempts, the first successful ascent of Aoraki / Mount Cook was made on Christmas Day 1894, by Tom Fyfe, Jack Clarke, and George Graham.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In December 1910, Freda Du Faur became the first woman to climb Aoraki / Mount Cook, and in 1913 her climbing party made the first ascents of the Footstool and Mount Sefton.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Mountaineering on the Aoraki / Mount Cook massif is a hazardous activity.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1982, Mark Inglis and his climbing partner were trapped in a snow cave for two weeks.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Other mountaineering routes include crossing the Aroarokaehe Range via the Copland Pass, and the Mount Cook Range via the Ball Pass.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The area was the training ground for Sir Edmund Hillary.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] On the opposite side of the Hooker Valley, Mount Ollivier was Sir Edmund Hillary's first major climb in 1939.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Since the establishment of a tramping track to Mueller Hut, not far below the summit, Ollivier is now one of the most accessible mountains in the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Another mountain popular for mountaineers of intermediate skills is Sebastopol, the closest mountain to Mount Cook Village.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] At 1,468 m (4,816 ft) in height, it is only 750 m (2,460 ft) above Mount Cook Village, with the lower half of the ascent following the Red Tarns tramping track.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Sebastopol offers one of a few view points taking in both the Hooker Valley and the Tasman Valley.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] There are 15 mountain huts in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park for the use of climbers and hunters.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Twelve of these are managed by the Department of Conservation, two belong to the New Zealand Deerstalkers Association and one, Caroline Hut, is privately owned by an alpine guiding company.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Another hut—Red Stag Hut—sits just outside the national park in the adjoining Te Kahui Kaupeka Conservation Park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Hooker Hut, built in 1910, is the oldest surviving hut in the national park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] It has been moved three times as the Hooker Glacier receded, then was removed and restored before being reassembled in a new location in 2021.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The oldest hut still in its original location is Sefton Bivouac, built in 1917.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In June 2012, an area of 4,367 km2 (1,686 sq mi) including Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park and the Mackenzie Basin was designated as the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve by the DarkSky International.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] At the time of the designation in 2012, the reserve was the largest in the world, and the only reserve of its type in the Southern Hemisphere.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The night sky brightness in the reserve ranks at a level 2 on the nine-level Bortle scale.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 2018 the Department of Conservation drafted a management plan for the park to consider how land, water, flora and fauna, aircraft and visitors to Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park could be managed over the following 10 years.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] However, review of the plan stopped in February 2019 to consider the ramifications of a Supreme Court decision involving Ngāi Tai, an Auckland iwi, who argued that DOC should consider the Treaty of Waitangi when granting concessions for commercial activities on conservation land.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Supreme Court found that "decisions to grant concessions to third parties would need to include asking whether the concession opportunities should be preserved for the economic benefit of Ngāi Tai and whether there was any basis for the preferential grant of concessions to Ngāi Tai".
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] DOC paused work on the management plan for Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park while it held discussions with Ngāi Tahu.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The formation of the draft management plan occurred at the same time as the number of visitors to Aoraki / Mount Cook Park was increasing dramatically.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Visitor numbers doubled between 2016 and 2019, reaching more than one million visits to Mount Cook Village, the gateway to the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Proposals to manage the huge number of tourists included a booking system, a park entrance fee, and a "park and ride" system to limit traffic in the village.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] A local Ngāi Tahu leader noted that Tourism New Zealand has been encouraging lots of people to come to the country without necessarily having the infrastructure in place".
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Department of Conservation had concerns about management of increasing quantities of human waste and litter in the village and in alpine huts, suggesting that visitors might be encouraged to take their litter away when they leave the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] A wide range of introduced animals are present in the park or in surrounding regions.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] These include stoats, red deer, possums, tahr and chamois.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Many of these animals pose significant threats to the flora and fauna of the park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1904, the Duke of Bedford gave five Himalayan tahr to the New Zealand Tourist Department.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The South Canterbury Acclimatisation Society released the animals at Governor's Bush in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park in December 1904.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1909, another eight tahr were released in the same area, and the population increased.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Tahr cause damage to alpine plants, leading to soil erosion, and from 1937 the government has attempted to control the spread and numbers of tahr.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Department of Conservation encourages hunting of tahr in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] In 1907, the Emperor of Austria presented the New Zealand government with a herd of eight chamois.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The animals were released in the Hooker valley near the Hermitage Hotel as protected game animals, and within a few years they had begun breeding and spreading along the length of the Southern Alps.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] By the 1930s chamois were acknowledged to be causing damage to the alpine environment, by eating native plants and by trampling vegetation and compacting the soil.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Protection was removed and control measures were created.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Today chamois can be hunted year-round in Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Research on lead toxicity in kea living at Aoraki / Mount Cook in the 1990s found that of 38 live kea tested, all were found to have detectable blood lead levels, 26 considered dangerously high.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Additional analysis of 15 dead kea sent to Massey University for diagnostic pathology between 1991 and 1997 found nine bodies to have lead blood levels consistent with causing death.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] After further testing in the 2000s found lead in kea, the Department of Conservation attempted to remove all sources of lead such as flashings and nail heads from buildings in Mount Cook Village.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] The Kea Conservation Trust has continued this work with funding from DOC.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] After extensive filming took place in national parks including Aoraki / Mount Cook for the *Lord of the Rings* trilogy, concerns about the possible effects of such activities on the environment were raised at a workshop in 2002.
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Aoraki / Mount Cook National Park has been used as a filming location for numerous films, including *Mulan* (2020), *Vertical Limit* (2000), *The Lord of the Rings* film series (2001–2003), *The Chronicles of Narnia* film series (2005–2010), and *A Wrinkle in Time* (2018).
[src:ashley-rakahuri-regional-park/mount-cook-national-park] Minas Tirith, the capital of Gondor in the fantasy adventure film series *The Lord of the Rings*, was filmed approximately 3 km (1.9 mi) away from Mount Cook Village.
